  "why": "The paper mutates inputs using image-level transformations (translation, rotation, brightness) — operations that are generally less sensitive to serialization-induced precision loss — and uses a conservative constraint strategy and Lp-norm validity checks to keep mutated images visually valid. However, the paper does not explicitly state any enforcement of input-format serialization constraints (e.g., clipping pixel values to integer [0,255] or explicit rounding when saving), nor does it claim to generate inputs directly as serialized artifacts. Therefore the method partially mitigates serialization sensitivity via choice of transformations and conservative validity checks but does not explicitly enforce all input-format constraints required for guaranteed failure reproducibility after serialization.",
  "evidence": "Page 4 (Section 2.1.2 Data Validity): \"In practice, the L_p norm [40] is usually used to guarantee the validity of the generated data by the existing DL testing and adversarial attack techniques. Specifically, given a valid input x, the new test case x' generated by adding some perturbations on x is considered as valid if ||x' - x||_p < epsilon, where epsilon is a safe radius.\"; Page 6 (Section 3.2 Distribution-Guided Test Generation): \"In this paper, we mainly focus on image classification tasks. ... We select the diverse image transformations (e.g., translation, rotation, brightness) used in DeepTest [54] and DeepHunter [63]. ... For each selected gene, the mutation randomly selects a transformation function to mutate it.\"; Page 6 (Section 3.2 Distribution-Guided Test Generation): \"To guarantee the validity of the generated inputs, we adopt the conservative strategy [63] that constrains the transformation with both 0 and infinity.\"; Page 9 (Section 4.2.2 RQ2: Efficiency of DistXplore): \"In order to evaluate the validity of the generated inputs, we conducted a manual investigation by randomly selecting 10,000 erroneous inputs from the testing outputs of each model and calculating the average validity ratio. The validity ratios were found to be 98.5%+, 96.5%+, 98.7%+, and 95.3%+ for MNIST, Fashion-MNIST, CIFAR-10, and SVHN datasets, respectively.\"; Note: the paper contains no explicit statement about clipping/rounding or other serialization-specific enforcement (e.g., ensuring integer pixel values in [0,255]) or about generating inputs directly in serialized formats."
